§. 5. Having thus rejected all sorts of commotion of the Blood, whether perform'd by way of Ebullition, or Fermentation, from being that which we are to define a Feaver by;

 yet since it is apparent that there is no Feaver, of what Type soever; existent without the presence of one of them; we are in the next place to consider, what it is that puts them into action: in doing which, a diligent Observation will easily informe us, that it is from the present temper of the Blood, and humour, that they are incited either to an Ebullition, or a Fermentation, according as the morbifick parts, that disturb it are by their Position adapted for expulsion, these exotick particles sent into it from some external cause, as Contagious vapors floating in the Air, immediate error in some of the six Non natural things, and (for reasons I shall declare in their proper place) rather choosing to extricate themselves by ebullition; as on the contrary, such impurities as have been contracted from any of these assisting parts of the Blood, we call humours, as they begin the Combate from somthing within, which, either from an undue retention of what should have been ejected, or a Preternatural readmission of what had been formerly cast out, is become Peccant; so it indeavors to expel those troublesome enemies by putting the whole mass into a violent commotion, but such as (being more proper for the expulsion of intestin enemies) discovers it self rather by the deliberate and gradual way of Fermentation, then the more violent one of ebullition.

 All which seriously considered, hath induced me, (rejecting the former Definitions) as most agreeable to those notions I have conceived of a Feaver, to adhere to the following.
